[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] A particular consequence of this is that the convolution can be viewed as a "smoothing" operation: the convolution of *f* and *g* is differentiable as many times as *f* and *g* are in total.
[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] These identities hold for example under the condition that *f* and *g* are absolutely integrable and at least one of them has an absolutely integrable (L1) weak derivative, as a consequence of Young's convolution inequality.
[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] These identities also hold much more broadly in the sense of tempered distributions if one of *f* or *g* is a rapidly decreasing tempered distribution, a compactly supported tempered distribution or a Schwartz function and the other is a tempered distribution.
[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] On the other hand, two positive integrable and infinitely differentiable functions may have a nowhere continuous convolution.
