[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] In fact, if *either* measure is absolutely continuous with respect to the Haar measure, then so is their convolution.
[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] If μ and ν are probability measures on the topological group (**R**,+), then the convolution *μ*∗*ν* is the probability distribution of the sum *X* + *Y* of two independent random variables *X* and *Y* whose respective distributions are μ and ν.
[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] Let (*X*, Δ, ∇, *ε*, *η*) be a bialgebra with comultiplication Δ, multiplication ∇, unit η, and counit *ε*.
[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] The convolution is a product defined on the endomorphism algebra End(*X*) as follows.
[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] The convolution appears notably in the definition of Hopf algebras (Kassel 1995, §III.3).
[src:convolution-reverb/convolution] Convolution and related operations are found in many applications in science, engineering and mathematics.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] In signal processing, a **finite impulse response** (**FIR**) **filter** is a filter whose impulse response (or response to any finite length input) is of *finite* duration, because it settles to zero in finite time.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] This is in contrast to infinite impulse response (IIR) filters, which may have internal feedback and may continue to respond indefinitely (usually decaying).
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The impulse response (that is, the output in response to a Kronecker delta input) of an Nth-order discrete-time FIR filter lasts exactly $N+1$ samples (from first nonzero element through last nonzero element) before it then settles to zero.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] FIR filters can be discrete-time or continuous-time, and digital or analog.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] This computation is also known as discrete convolution.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The ${\textstyle x[n-i]}$ in these terms are commonly referred to as *taps*, based on the structure of a tapped delay line that in many implementations or block diagrams provides the delayed inputs to the multiplication operations.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] One may speak of a *5th order/6-tap filter*, for instance.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The impulse response of the filter as defined is nonzero over a finite duration.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] If an FIR filter is non-causal, the range of nonzero values in its impulse response can start before $n=0$ , with the defining formula appropriately generalized.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] An FIR filter has a number of useful properties which sometimes make it preferable to an infinite impulse response (IIR) filter.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The main disadvantage of FIR filters is that considerably more computation power in a general purpose processor is required compared to an IIR filter with similar sharpness or selectivity, especially when low frequency (relative to the sample rate) cutoffs are needed.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] However, many digital signal processors provide specialized hardware features to make FIR filters approximately as efficient as IIR for many applications.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] where operators ${\mathcal {F}}$ and ${\mathcal {F}}^{-1}$ respectively denote the discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT) and its inverse.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Therefore, the complex-valued, multiplicative function $H(\omega )$ is the filter's frequency response.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] where the added subscript denotes $2\pi$ -periodicity.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Here $\omega$ represents frequency in normalized units (*radians per sample*).
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The function $H_{2\pi }(2\pi f')$ has a periodicity of 1 with $f'$ in units of *cycles per sample*, which is favored by many filter design applications.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Conversely, if one wants to design a filter for ordinary frequencies $f_{1},$ $f_{2},$ etc., using an application that expects *cycles per sample*, one would enter $f_{1}/f_{s},$ $f_{2}/f_{s},$ etc.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] FIR filters are designed by finding the coefficients and filter order that meet certain specifications, which can be in the time domain (e.g. a matched filter) or the frequency domain (most common).
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Matched filters perform a cross-correlation between the input signal and a known pulse shape.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The FIR convolution is a cross-correlation between the input signal and a time-reversed copy of the impulse response.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Therefore, the matched filter's impulse response is "designed" by sampling the known pulse-shape and using those samples in reverse order as the coefficients of the filter.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Parks–McClellan method (also known as the equiripple, optimal, or minimax method).
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The Remez exchange algorithm is commonly used to find an optimal equiripple set of coefficients.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Here the user specifies a desired frequency response, a weighting function for errors from this response, and a filter order *N*.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The algorithm then finds the set of ${\textstyle N+1}$ coefficients that minimize the maximum deviation from the ideal.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Intuitively, this finds the filter that is as close as possible to the desired response given that only ${\textstyle N+1}$ coefficients can be used.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] This method is particularly easy in practice since at least one text includes a program that takes the desired filter and *N*, and returns the optimum coefficients.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Equiripple FIR filters can be designed using the DFT algorithms as well.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The DFT of an initial filter design is computed using the FFT algorithm (if an initial estimate is not available, h[n]=delta[n] can be used).
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] In the Fourier domain, or DFT domain, the frequency response is corrected according to the desired specs, and the inverse DFT is then computed.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] In the time-domain, only the first N coefficients are kept (the other coefficients are set to zero).
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The process is then repeated iteratively: the DFT is computed once again, correction applied in the frequency domain and so on.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Software packages such as MATLAB, GNU Octave, Scilab, and SciPy provide convenient ways to apply these different methods.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] In the window design method, one first designs an ideal IIR filter and then truncates the infinite impulse response by multiplying it with a finite length window function.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The result is a finite impulse response filter whose frequency response is modified from that of the IIR filter.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Multiplying the infinite impulse by the window function in the time domain results in the frequency response of the IIR being convolved with the Fourier transform (or DTFT) of the window function.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] If the window's main lobe is narrow, the composite frequency response remains close to that of the ideal IIR filter.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The ideal frequency response is often an ideal, rectangular low-pass, and the corresponding IIR is a sinc function.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The result of the frequency domain convolution is that the edges of the rectangle are tapered, and ripples appear in the passband and stopband.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Working backward, one can specify the slope (or width) of the tapered region (*transition band*) and the height of the ripples, and thereby derive the frequency-domain parameters of an appropriate window function.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Continuing backward to an impulse response can be done by iterating a filter design program to find the minimum filter order.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Another method is to restrict the solution set to the parametric family of Kaiser windows, which provides closed form relationships between the time-domain and frequency domain parameters.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] In general, that method will not achieve the minimum possible filter order, but it is particularly convenient for automated applications that require dynamic, on-the-fly, filter design.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The window design method is also advantageous for creating efficient half-band filters, because the corresponding sinc function is zero at every other sample point (except the center one).
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The product with the window function does not alter the zeros, so almost half of the coefficients of the final impulse response are zero.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] An appropriate implementation of the FIR calculations can exploit that property to double the filter's efficiency.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] To design FIR filter in the MSE sense, we minimize the mean square error between the filter we obtained and the desired filter.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] A moving average filter is a very simple FIR filter.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] It is sometimes called a boxcar filter, especially when followed by decimation, or a sinc-in-frequency.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The block diagram on the right shows the second-order moving-average filter discussed below.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The next figure shows the corresponding pole–zero diagram.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] Zero frequency (DC) corresponds to (1, 0), positive frequencies advancing counterclockwise around the circle to the Nyquist frequency at (−1, 0).
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The magnitude and phase components of ${\textstyle H\left(e^{j\omega }\right)}$ are plotted in the figure.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] But plots like these can also be generated by doing a discrete Fourier transform (DFT) of the impulse response.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] And because of symmetry, filter design or viewing software often displays only the [0, π] region.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The magnitude plot indicates that the moving-average filter passes low frequencies with a gain near 1 and attenuates high frequencies, and is thus a crude low-pass filter.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The phase plot is linear except for discontinuities at the two frequencies where the magnitude goes to zero.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] The size of the discontinuities is π, representing a sign reversal.
[src:convolution-reverb/finite-impulse-response] They do not affect the property of linear phase, as illustrated in the final figure.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] In signal processing and control theory, the **impulse response**, or **impulse response function** (**IRF**), of a dynamic system is its output when presented with a brief input signal, called an impulse (δ(*t*)).
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] More generally, an impulse response is the reaction of any dynamic system in response to some external change.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] In both cases, the impulse response describes the reaction of the system as a function of time (or possibly as a function of some other independent variable that parameterizes the dynamic behavior of the system).
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] In all these cases, the dynamic system and its impulse response may be actual physical objects, or may be mathematical systems of equations describing such objects.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Since the impulse function contains all frequencies (see the Fourier transform of the Dirac delta function, showing infinite frequency bandwidth that the Dirac delta function has), the impulse response defines the response of a linear time-invariant system for all frequencies.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Mathematically, how the impulse is described depends on whether the system is modeled in discrete or continuous time.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The impulse can be modeled as a Dirac delta function for continuous-time systems, or as the discrete unit sample function for discrete-time systems.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The Dirac delta represents the limiting case of a pulse made very short in time while maintaining its area or integral (thus giving an infinitely high peak).
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] While this is impossible in any real system, it is a useful idealization.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] In Fourier analysis theory, such an impulse comprises equal portions of all possible excitation frequencies, which makes it a convenient test probe.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Any system in a large class known as *linear, time-invariant* (LTI) is completely characterized by its impulse response.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] That is, for any input, the output can be calculated in terms of the input and the impulse response.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] (See LTI system theory.) The impulse response of a linear transformation is the image of Dirac's delta function under the transformation, analogous to the fundamental solution of a partial differential operator.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] It is usually easier to analyze systems using transfer functions as opposed to impulse responses.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The transfer function is the Laplace transform of the impulse response.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The Laplace transform of a system's output may be determined by the multiplication of the transfer function with the input's Laplace transform in the complex plane, also known as the frequency domain.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] An inverse Laplace transform of this result will yield the output in the time domain.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] To determine an output directly in the time domain requires the convolution of the input with the impulse response.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] When the transfer function and the Laplace transform of the input are known, this convolution may be more complicated than the alternative of multiplying two functions in the frequency domain.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The impulse response, considered as a Green's function, can be thought of as an "influence function": how a point of input influences output.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] In practice, it is not possible to perturb a system with a perfect impulse.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] One can use a brief pulse as a first approximation.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Limitations of this approach include the duration of the pulse and its magnitude.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The response can be close, compared to the ideal case, provided the pulse is short enough.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Additionally, in many systems, a pulse of large intensity may drive the system into the nonlinear regime.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Other methods exist to construct an impulse response.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The impulse response can be calculated from the input and output of a system driven with a pseudo-random sequence, such as maximum length sequences.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Another approach is to take a sine sweep measurement and process the result to get the impulse response.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Impulse response loudspeaker testing was first developed in the 1970s.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Loudspeakers suffer from phase inaccuracy (delayed frequencies) which can be caused by passive crossovers, resonance, cone momentum, the internal volume, and vibrating enclosure panels.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The impulse response can be used to indicate when such inaccuracies can be improved by different materials, enclosures or crossovers.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Loudspeakers have a physical limit to their power output, thus the input amplitude must be limited to maintain linearity.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] This limitation led to the use of inputs like maximum length sequences in obtaining the impulse response.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Impulse response analysis is a major facet of radar, ultrasound imaging, and many areas of digital signal processing.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] An interesting example is found in broadband internet connections.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Digital subscriber line service providers use adaptive equalization to compensate for signal distortion and interference from using copper phone lines for transmission.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] In control theory the impulse response is the response of a system to a Dirac delta input.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] This proves useful in the analysis of dynamic systems; the Laplace transform of the delta function is 1, so the impulse response is equivalent to the inverse Laplace transform of the system's transfer function.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] In acoustic and audio settings, impulse responses can be used to capture the acoustic characteristics of many things.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The reverb at a location, the body of an instrument, certain analog audio equipment, and amplifiers are all emulated by impulse responses.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] The impulse is convolved with a dry signal in software, often to create the effect of a physical recording.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Various packages containing impulse responses from specific locations are available online.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] In economics, and especially in contemporary macroeconomic modeling, impulse response functions are used to describe how the economy reacts over time to exogenous impulses, which economists usually call shocks, and are often modeled in the context of a vector autoregression.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Impulse response functions describe the reaction of endogenous macroeconomic variables such as output, consumption, investment, and employment at the time of the shock and over subsequent points in time.
[src:convolution-reverb/impulse-response] Recently, asymmetric impulse response functions have been suggested in the literature that separate the impact of a positive shock from a negative one.
[src:convolution-reverb/overlap-add-method] This article uses common abstract notations, such as ${\textstyle y(t)=x(t)*h(t),}$ or ${\textstyle y(t)={\mathcal {H}}\{x(t)\},}$ in which it is understood that the functions should be thought of in their totality, rather than at specific instants ${\textstyle t}$ (see Convolution#Notation).
[src:convolution-reverb/overlap-add-method] When the DFT and IDFT are implemented by the FFT algorithm, the pseudocode above requires about **N (log2(N) + 1)** complex multiplications for the FFT, product of arrays, and IFFT.
[src:convolution-reverb/overlap-add-method] For example, when $M=201$ and $N=1024,$ **Eq.3** equals $13.67,$ whereas direct evaluation of **Eq.1** would require up to $201$ complex multiplications per output sample, the worst case being when both x and h are complex-valued.
[src:convolution-reverb/overlap-add-method] Also note that for any given $M,$ **Eq.3** has a minimum with respect to $N.$ Figure 2 is a graph of the values of N that minimize **Eq.3** for a range of filter lengths ( M ).
[src:convolution-reverb/overlap-add-method] Instead of **Eq.1**, we can also consider applying **Eq.2** to a long sequence of length $N_{x}$ samples.
[src:convolution-reverb/overlap-add-method] Hence the *cost* of the overlap–add method scales almost as $O\left(N_{x}\log _{2}N\right)$ while the cost of a single, large circular convolution is almost $O\left(N_{x}\log _{2}N_{x}\right)$ .
[src:convolution-reverb/overlap-add-method] The two methods are also compared in Figure 3, created by MATLAB simulation.
[src:convolution-reverb/overlap-add-method] The contours are lines of constant ratio of the times it takes to perform both methods.
[src:convolution-reverb/overlap-add-method] When the overlap-add method is faster, the ratio exceeds 1, and ratios as high as 3 are seen.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] For frequencies under the Schroeder frequency, certain wavelengths of sound will build up as resonances within the boundaries of the room, and the resonating frequencies can be determined using the room's dimensions.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] Modes can occur in all three dimensions of a room.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] Axial modes are one-dimensional and build up between one set of parallel walls.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] Tangential modes are two-dimensional and involve four walls bounding the space perpendicular to each other.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] Finally, oblique modes concern all walls within the simplified rectilinear room.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] A modal density analysis method using concepts from psychoacoustics, the "Bonello criterion", analyzes the first 48 room modes and plots the number of modes in each one-third of an octave.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] The curve increases monotonically (each one-third of an octave must have more modes than the preceding one).
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] Other systems to determine correct room ratios have more recently been developed.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] After determining the best dimensions of the room, using the modal density criteria, the next step is to find the correct reverberation time.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] The most appropriate reverberation time depends on the use of the room.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] RT60 is a measure of reverberation time.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] Times about 1.5 to 2 seconds are needed for opera theaters and concert halls.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] For broadcasting and recording studios and conference rooms, values under one second are frequently used.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] The recommended reverberation time is always a function of the volume of the room.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] Ideally, the RT60 should have about the same value at all frequencies from 30 to 12,000 Hz.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] To get the desired RT60, several acoustics materials can be used as described in several books.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] A valuable simplification of the task was proposed by Oscar Bonello in 1979.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] It consists of using standard acoustic panels of 1 m2 hung from the walls of the room (only if the panels are parallel).
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] These panels use a combination of three Helmholtz resonators and a wooden resonant panel.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] This system gives a large acoustic absorption at low frequencies (under 500 Hz) and reduces at high frequencies to compensate for the typical absorption by people, lateral surfaces, ceilings, etc.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] In reality, there are some properties of acoustics that affect the acoustic space.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] These properties can either improve the quality of the sound or interfere with the sound.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] The application of acoustic space is very useful in architecture.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] Some kinds of architecture need a proficient design to bring out the best performances.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] For example, concert halls, auditoriums, theaters, or even cathedrals.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] The task of room acoustics is to influence these parameters by designing the room in such a way that the acoustic properties of the room are maximized for its intended use.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] However, not all venues are designed with acoustics in mind.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] In this case, speaker placement will play a decisive role in the movement of sound waves, affecting clarity, loudness and overall sound quality.
[src:convolution-reverb/room-acoustics] Since the acoustic properties of rooms for different applications are almost incompatible, it is hardly possible to create a universal room that combines good speech intelligibility and good spatial music perception.
